SIMPLE: medley
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Medley
<hw>Med"ley</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Medleys</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[OE. <ets>medlee</ets>, OF.
<ets>mesl⟦eacute⟧e</ets>, <ets>medl⟦eacute⟧e</ets>,
<ets>mell⟦eacute⟧e</ets>, F. <ets>m⟦ecir⟧l⟦eacute⟧e</ets>. See
<er>Meddle</er>, and cf. <er>Mel⟦eacute⟧e</er>, <er>Mellay</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>A mixture; a mingled and confused mass of ingredients,
usually inharmonious; a jumble; a hodgepodge; -- often used
contemptuously.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>This <qex>medley</qex> of philosophy and war.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Love is a <qex>medley</qex> of endearments, jars,⟦br⟧
Suspicions, reconcilements, wars.</q> <rj><qau>W. Walsh.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>The confusion of a hand to hand battle; a brisk,
hand to hand engagement; a m⟦ecir⟧l⟦eacute⟧e.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark>
<rj><au>Holland.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <fld>(Mus.)</fld> <def>A composition of passages detached
from several different compositions; a potpourri.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ <xex>Medley</xex> is usually applied to vocal,
<contr>potpourri</contr> to instrumental, compositions.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>A cloth of mixed colors.</def>
<rj><au>Fuller.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medley</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Medley
<hw>Med"ley</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>Mixed; of mixed
material or color.</def> <mark>[Obs.]</mark> ⟦ldquo⟧A <xex>medl⟦eacute⟧
coat</xex>.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Mingled; confused.</def>
<rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Medly</ent>⟦br⟧
